abstract: LONDON, Oct, 1. This morning's Standard publishes the following special dispatch from Sophia dated Sunday evening, Sept. 30: "Trustworthy information has been received here that Osman Pasha has repulsed a RussoRoumanian attack on his front and left, inflicting heavy losses. It is also said that he attacked the Russians on the Lovatz road and rocovered several positions."

abstract: Never heretofore has there been so much rowing in a single day on the Harlem River as there was yesterday. It began at 9 A.M. and lasted till sunset. The Fall Regatta of the Harlem Regatta Association was the occasion for this unusual aquatic display, which took in, not merely all the clubs on the Harlem, but most of the well-known rowing associations in the vicinity of New-York and some of more remote habitations.

abstract: If this country is to realize the full advantages of its bounteous wheat crop and the exceptional condition of the British market, the idea of making great fortunes within the next few months must be abandoned. abstract: Archbishop Bayley, of Baltimore, died in Newark, N.J., yesterday morning. He was born in this City on Aug. 23, 1814. His father was a wellknown physician of New-York, and was for a long period the head of the medical staff of the Bloomingdale Lunatic Asylum. His grandfather, Dr. Richard Bayley, a native of Fairfield, Conn., and a graduate of the medical schools and hospitals of London, was a distinguished physician of his day.

abstract: BOSTON,Mass, Oct. 5 The proceedings of the third day of the Episcopal General Convention, in Emmanuel Church, were opened with prayer and singing by the choir of the Church of the Advent. The record of the proceedings of the second day were read and approved.

abstract: Scenes of an ominous and rather startling character were enacted among the Penitentiary convicts on Blackwell's Island during the early part of last week. abstract: Numerous reports of anticipated trouble with the Indians at Sitka and appeals for troops to protect the white residents having been forwarded to Washington, the revenue cutter under command of Capt. Wight found everything going on in the usual peace.

abstract: GENERAL: This command moved rapidly to Snake Creek, striking a fresh trail of the hostile Nez Perces, coming out of the Bear Paw Mountains, at 7 o'clock on the 30th ult. We met and surprised a camp at 8 o'clock, capturing the larger part of their herd, about 600 horses, mules and ponies. The engagement was quite severe, and inclosed is the list of our killed and wounded.

abstract: LONDON, Oct. 8. A single-scull race for 400 and the championship of England was rowed on the Thames to-day, from Putney to Mortlake, between J. Higgins, of London, and R. Boyd, of Newcastle. The race was won by Higgins by six lengths. The reported time is 24 minutes 10 seconds, but of course this is not at all accurate.

abstract: LONDON, Oct. 28. A Paris dispatch to Reuter's Telegram Company says M. Rouher has had an attack of apoplexy, but, notwithstanding some newspaper statements to the contrary, is now nearly well again. The Francais, the Duke de Broglie's organ, yesterday stated that the Ministers were prepared to meet the Chambers and defend their policy, but at the same time were ready to resign should President MacMahon think it his duty to summon other counselors.

abstract: One morning two or three days ago a middleaged man with a sore thumb and a look of anticipation entered Justice Goodwin's office and softly sat down. He put his hat on the floor; sat up very erect, and for three straight hours hardly moved a finger. At noon, as the Justice was ready to go, he asked the strange man if he wanted anythinng. "Yaw," he calmly answered.
